{{Infobox book | name = Bacon: A Love Story | image = Bacon A Love Story.jpg | caption = | alt = Book cover for Bacon: A Love Story. In the center is an illustration of a steam slab of bacon. | author = [[Heather Lauer]] | country = United States | language = English | subject = [[Bacon]] | genre = [[Non-fiction]] | publisher = [[William Morrow and Company|William Morrow]] | pub_date = May 2009 | media_type = Hardback | pages = 224 | isbn = 978-0-06-170428-4 | oclc = | dewey = | congress = }} '''''Bacon: A Love Story, A Salty Survey of Everybody's Favorite Meat''''' is a 2009<ref>{{cite news | last =Silence | first =Michael | title =Coming soon: 'Bacon: A Love Story' | work =[[Knoxville News Sentinel]] | publisher =Knoxville News Sentinel Co. | date =January 12, 2009 |page=Blogs; Section: No Silence Here }}</ref> [[non-fiction]] book about [[bacon]], written by American writer [[Heather Lauer]]. Lauer started the blog ''Bacon Unwrapped'' and a [[Social networking service|social networking]] site about bacon in 2005, after the idea came to her while she was out drinking with her two brothers; her online success inspired her to write the book, which describes [[curing (food preservation)|curing]] and cooking bacon, gives over 20 bacon recipes, and analyzes the impact of bacon on [[popular culture]]. The text is interspersed with facts about bacon and bacon-related quips from comedian [[Jim Gaffigan]].
The book had a generally positive reception; ''[[The Sacramento Bee]]'' called it "entertaining and informational".<ref name="pierleoni" /> The ''[[Toronto Star]]'' and ''The Sacramento Bee'' recommended it as a [[Father's Day]] gift.<ref name="pierleoni" /><ref name="zekas" /> ''[[The Portsmouth Herald]]'' and ''[[The Arizona Republic]]'' highlighted the book on lists of summer reading recommendations.<ref name="forrest" /><ref name="turnpages" /> ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'' wrote that bacon lovers would enjoy the book, but other readers may not so much.<ref name="publishers" />
==Content summary== ''Bacon: A Love Story'' contains information on cooking and [[curing (food preservation)|curing]] bacon,<ref name="spartos" /> including "time-honored methods and traditions".<ref name="gatehouse">{{cite news | last =GateHouse News Service | title =Food for Thought: Pick vegetables good for grilling | work =[[The Bulletin (Norwich)|Norwich Bulletin]]|location=[[Norwich, Connecticut]] | date =May 5, 2009 }}</ref> The book analyzes how bacon has affected [[popular culture]].<ref name="pierleoni" /> Lauer includes information on chefs who love of bacon and venues that serve the product throughout the United States.<ref name="gatehouse" /> The book contains over 20 recipes for dishes made with bacon,<ref name="gatehouse" /> including Bacon [[Bloody Mary (cocktail)|Bloody Mary]], Bacon-Wrapped [[Tater Tots]], Bacon Bleu Salad, and bacon brownies.<ref name="spartos" /><ref>{{cite news | last =Lapan | first =Tovin | title =Wrapped up in bacon: We're hog wild for this fatty meat, but is the trend more smoke than sizzle? | work =[[U-T San Diego|The San Diego Union-Tribune]] | publisher =Union-Tribune Publishing Co. | page =E-1 | date =June 17, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last =Southern Illinoisan staff | title =Bacon and Bleu Salad | work =[[The Southern Illinoisan]]|location=[[Carbondale, Illinois]] | page =2 | date =September 16, 2009}}</ref> Another recipe is Bristol Bacon by chef Duncan Bristol, who owns the restaurant Brick 29 in [[Nampa, Idaho]].<ref>{{cite news | last =Oland | first =Dana | title =Area restaurants expand their business without adding seats | work =[[Idaho Statesman]]|location=[[Boise, Idaho]] | page =19 | date =June 19, 2009}}</ref> Interspersed throughout the book are bits about bacon from comedian [[Jim Gaffigan]], and random information such as that "Cracker Barrel serves 124 million slices of bacon per year".<ref name="byrne">{{cite news | last =Byrne | first =Kerry J. | title =Fast Food | work =[[Boston Herald]]|location=[[Boston]], Massachusetts | at =Section: Food | date =July 22, 2009 }}</ref> Lauer notes, "[[Speck]] is the direct German translation of the word 'bacon{{' "}}, and observes that the word "creates cross-cultural confusion".<ref>{{cite news | first =Bill |last=Wade | title =Speck is a smokin' variation of prosciutto | work =[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|location=[[Pittsburgh]], Pennsylvania | page =11 | date =September 23, 2009 |url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/09266/998436-478.stm|accessdate=2009-12-11}}</ref> The book's "Bacon 411" section provides further information on the product.<ref name="gatehouse" />
==Background== Before the book's publication, Heather Lauer was a public affairs consultant in [[Arizona]].<ref name="abraham">{{cite news | last =Abraham | first =Lisa | title =Bacon comes home&nbsp;– Old favorite tastes even better when you do the curing yourself | work =[[Akron Beacon Journal]]|location=[[Akron, Ohio]] | page =D1 | date =August 12, 2009 }}</ref> She hatched the idea to write a book about bacon after going out for cocktails with her two brothers in 2005.<ref name="abraham" /> Lauer explained to ''[[The Arizona Republic]]'': "I was out drinking with my brothers one night, and the topic of bacon came up. We had eaten bacon as kids, and bacon was a special thing on Sunday mornings. Somehow, the idea came up about how funny it would be to start a blog about bacon&nbsp;... I took it and ran with it."<ref>{{cite news | last =Cordova | first =Randy | title =Phoenix bacon blogger publishes book | work =[[The Arizona Republic]]|location=[[Phoenix, Arizona]] | publisher =www.azcentral.com | date =June 9, 2009 | url =http://www.azcentral.com/community/phoenix/articles/2009/06/09/20090609baconlady0609.html | accessdate = 2009-12-11 }}</ref> She began the blog ''Bacon Unwrapped'',<ref>{{cite news | last =Fraser | first =Garnet | title =Why the zeitgeist suddenly smells so wonderful | work =[[Toronto Star]] | publisher =Toronto Star Newspapers Limited | page =E12 | date =February 15, 2009|url=https://www.thestar.com/article/587604|accessdate=2009-12-11 }}</ref> at www.baconunwrapped.com,<ref name="pierleoni">{{cite news | last =Pierleoni | first =Allen | title =You know Dad loves to read&nbsp;– Father's Day gift book ideas run the gamut: Pictures, essays, humor, food&nbsp;– and even some useful stuff | work =[[The Sacramento Bee]] | page =D3 | date =May 25, 2009 }}</ref><ref name="forrest" /> and a [[Social networking service|social networking]] site about bacon at baconnation.ning.com in 2005.<ref name="abraham" />
Lauer thought that the surge in interest in bacon products prior to the book's publication was "media driven".<ref name="spartos">{{cite news | last =Spartos | first =Carlos | title =Bacon whoopee!&nbsp;– NYC hog wild for cured meat; Taken with bacon&nbsp;– Have pork product, will travel | work =[[New York Post]] | page =041 | date =March 25, 2009 |url=http://www.nypost.com/p/lifestyle/food/item_SkjRdKXPqWVpbnweOHhgWL|accessdate=2009-12-11}}</ref> She noted that a response to [[political correctness]] as related to cooking and food consumption may have driven interest in the product.<ref name="spartos" /> Lauer said that bacon seems to be "the one thing that people are unwilling to give up".<ref name="spartos" /> In a post of her blog in March 2009, Lauer lamented those that were willing to posit an end to the trend of interest in bacon.<ref name="spartos" /> She commented, "Bacon is something that everybody is familiar with and most people grew up eating. It has a comfort aspect to it and a familiarity. It's also got an addictive aspect to it&nbsp;— that sweet and salty combination of flavors."<ref name="abraham" /> She asserted that interest in the product is as much due to the culture surrounding it as to bacon itself.<ref name="abraham" /> "Current food trends focus on eating real and eating local, and there's nothing more real than a delicious strip of bacon. In many U.S. cities, local producers and chefs are making a name for themselves because of bacon," said Lauer.<ref name="asa">{{cite news | last =Asa | first =Rick | title =All hail bacon | work =[[Chicago Tribune]]|location=[[Chicago]], Illinois | publisher =Chicago Tribune Company | page =6; Section: Good Eating | date =October 28, 2009 }}</ref> She stated that "most chefs would admit that bacon has long been one of their secret weapons in the kitchen."<ref name="asa" /> The book was marketed as the "most comprehensive book about bacon to date".<ref name="spartos" /> Lauer promoted her book in a September 2009 appearance as a co-host at the Blue Ribbon Bacon Tour in [[Pennsylvania]], hosted by fellow bacon blogger Jason Mosley (Mr. Baconpants, at mrbaconpants.com).<ref>{{cite news | last =Batz Jr. | first =Bob | title =Bacon Tour your chance to pig out | work =[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|location=[[Pittsburgh]], Pennsylvania | page =E-1 | date =September 24, 2009|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/09267/1000308-34.stm|accessdate=2009-12-11 }}</ref>
==Reception== Writing for ''[[The Sacramento Bee]]'', Allen Pierleoni recommended the book as a gift for [[Father's Day]], and called the work "entertaining and informational, full of anecdotes, history, recipes and explanations of what pork belly has brought to the popular culture".<ref name="pierleoni" /> Rita Zekas of the ''[[Toronto Star]]'' also recommended the book as a Father's Day gift.<ref name="zekas">{{cite news | last =Zekas | first =Rita | title =Great gifts for dad | work =[[Toronto Star]] | publisher =www.thestar.com | date =June 19, 2009 | url =https://www.thestar.com/printArticle/652472 | accessdate = 2009-12-11 }}</ref> Kerry J. Byrne noted that the book covers "everything from bacon-curing methods to bacon blogs" and includes "easy recipes".<ref name="byrne" /> ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'' reviewed called the book a "voluminous look at all things bacon";<ref name="publishers">{{cite news | last =Publishers Weekly staff | title =Bacon: A Salty Survey of Everybody's Favorite Meat | work =[[Publishers Weekly]] | publisher =Reed Elsevier Inc. | page =Lifestyle | date =May 11, 2009 }}</ref> the review concluded, "Readers who, like Lauer, possess a borderline-obsessive love for bacon are likely to embrace this as their new Bible, but anyone else will quickly get their fill."<ref name="publishers" /> Rachel Forrest of ''[[The Portsmouth Herald]]'' recommended the book in her "Annual Summer Reading List for [[Foodie]]s".<ref name="forrest">{{cite news | last =Forrest | first =Rachel | title =Annual Summer Reading List for Foodies | work =[[The Portsmouth Herald]] | publisher =www.seacoastonline.com | date =June 3, 2009 | url =http://www.seacoastonline.com/articles/20090603-LIFE-906030304 | accessdate = 2009-12-11}}</ref> "Another of my favorites this year is 'Bacon: A Love Story: A Salty Survey of Everybody's Favorite Meat' by Heather Lauer. A book all about bacon&nbsp;... she profiles chefs that use it, odd finds across the nation and plenty of recipes," commented Forrest.<ref name="forrest" /> ''[[The Arizona Republic]]'' highlighted the book among its selection of "Books to help turn pages of summer".<ref name="turnpages">{{cite news | last =The Arizona Republic staff | title =Books to help turn pages of summer | work =[[The Arizona Republic]] | publisher =www.azcentral.com | page =Non-fiction | date =May 5, 2009 | url =http://www.azcentral.com/arizonarepublic/ae/articles/2009/05/05/20090505summerbooks0503thrillers.html | accessdate =2009-12-11}}</ref>
