{{good article}}
{{Infobox person
| name        = George Pickingill
| image       = George Pickingill, Cunning Man.jpg
| caption     = Photograph allegedly of Pickingill taken in the late nineteenth or early twentieth century.{{efn|The original copy of this photograph was owned by Lillian Garner, who claimed that it was of George Pickingill and who allowed for it to be first published by Eric Maple; in 1977 she gave her original copy of the photograph to Michael Howard.{{sfn|Howard|2011|p=114}} In a July 1984 issue of ''Insight'' magazine, a letter was published by John Pope stating that "The photograph purporting to be Old George Pickingill is in fact a photo of Alf Cavill, a station porter at [[Elstree]], taken in the early 1960s. Alf is now dead, but he was no witch, and laughed over the photograph when he saw it."{{sfn|Phillips|2004}} Wiccan historian Julia Phillips cautioned however that "a very respected Craft authority has told me that he believes the photo, which is in his possession, to be of Pickingill, and I have no reason to disbelieve him."{{sfn|Phillips|2004}} }}
| birth_name  = 
| image_size  = 200 px
| birth_date  = Circa 1816
| birth_place = [[Hockley]], Essex 
| death_date  = 10 April 1909
| death_place = [[Canewdon]], Essex
| occupation  = Cunning man, farm labourer
| spouse      = Sarah Ann Bateman <small>(m. 1856–87)</small>
| children    = Martha Ann, Charles Frederick, Mary Ann, George
| parents     = Charles Pickingill, Susannah Cudner
