{{Other uses|Rice (disambiguation)}} {{Refimprove|date=December 2014}} {{Expert needed|Medicine|talk=Issue|date=February 2015}} <!--Basically see the entire talk page (2 topics), the icing sounds excessive to me as well--> {{Infobox medical intervention | name = RICIN | image = | caption = | alt = | pronounce = | synonyms = | ICD10 = | ICD9 = | ICD9unlinked = | CPT = | MeshID = | LOINC = | other_codes = | MedlinePlus = | eMedicine = }}
'''RICE''' is a [[mnemonic]] for four elements of treatment for [[soft tissue injury|soft tissue injuries]] – an [[acronym]] for '''[[Relaxation technique|rest]]''', '''[[Cryotherapy#Ice pack therapy|ice]]''', '''[[Cold compression therapy|compression]]''' and '''[[Anatomical terms of motion#Elevation and depression|elevation]]'''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sportsmedicine.about.com/cs/rehab/a/rice.htm |title=R.I.C.E - Best for Acute Injuries |accessdate=2007-08-15 |work=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://med.umich.edu/1libr/sma/sma_rice_sma.htm |title=Sports Medicine Advisor 2005.4: RICE: Rest, Ice, Compression, and Elevation for Injuries |accessdate=2007-08-15 |work= |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070911021102/http://med.umich.edu/1libr/sma/sma_rice_sma.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-09-11}}</ref><ref>{{MedicalMnemonics|235|||}}</ref> The mnemonic was introduced by Gabe Mirkin in Sportsmedicine Book ({{ISBN|978-0316574365}}) in year 1978. However, he has since recanted his support for the regimen. On March 16, 2014, he wrote "Coaches have used my 'RICE' guideline for decades, but now it appears that both Ice and complete Rest may delay healing, instead of helping. In a recent study, athletes were told to exercise so intensely that they developed severe muscle damage that caused extensive muscle soreness. Although cooling delayed swelling, it did not hasten recovery from this muscle damage."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://drmirkin.com/fitness/why-ice-delays-recovery.html |title=Why Ice Delays Recovery |accessdate=2014-10-24 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20140629055909/http://drmirkin.com/fitness/why-ice-delays-recovery.html|archivedate=29 June 2014 }}</ref>
RICE is considered a [[first-aid]] treatment, rather than a cure for soft tissue injuries. The aim is to manage discomfort and internal bleeding.<ref name="pmid17512485">{{cite journal |vauthors=Järvinen TA, Järvinen TL, Kääriäinen M, etal |title=Muscle injuries: optimising recovery |journal=Best practice & research. Clinical rheumatology |volume=21 |issue=2 |pages=317–31 |year=2007 |pmid=17512485 |doi=10.1016/j.berh.2006.12.004}}</ref>
== Evidence == There is not enough evidence from randomized controlled trials to determine the true effectiveness of RICE therapy for acute ankle sprains. Treatment decisions for ankle sprains must be made on an individual basis and relies on expert opinions and national guidelines.<ref name="pmid22889660">{{cite journal |vauthors=van den Bekerom MP, Struijs PA, Blankevoort L, Welling L, van Dijk CN, Kerkhoffs GM|title=What is the evidence for rest, ice, compression, and elevation therapy in the treatment of ankle sprains in adults? |journal=Journal of Athletic Training |volume=47 |issue=4 |pages=435–43 |year=2012 |pmid=22889660 |doi=10.4085/1062-6050-47.4.14 |pmc=3396304}}</ref>
== Primary four terms ==
=== Rest === Rest is a key component of repairing the body. Without rest, continual strain is placed on the affected area that is injured, leading to increased inflammation, pain, and possible further injury. Rest is recommended during the initial 24–48 hours after an injury, but after that modified activities can be started.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://education.pthealth.ca/Injury-Care/R-I-C-E/a~1228/article.html|title=Physiotherapy|access-date=2016-07-11}}</ref> Additionally, some soft tissue injuries will take longer to heal without rest. There is also a risk of abnormal repair or chronic inflammation resulting from a failure to rest. In general, the period of rest should be long enough that the patient is able to use the affected limb with the majority of function restored and pain essentially gone. {{citation needed|date=November 2013}}
=== Ice === Ice is excellent at reducing the inflammatory response and pain associated with heat generated by increased blood flow and/or blood loss.<ref name="Sprains and strains">{{cite web|title=Sprains and strains|url=http://www.umm.edu/altmed/articles/sprains-and-000157.htm|accessdate=2011}}</ref> A good method is apply ice for 20 minutes of each hour. Other recommendations are an alternation of ice and no-ice for 15–20 minutes each, for a 48-hour period.<ref>[http://www.uofmhealth.org/health-library/tw4354spec#tp21229 ''RICE: Rest, Ice, Compression, and Elevation for Injuries''] on the website of the [[University of Michigan]] Health System, retrieved 28 July 2008</ref> To prevent localised [[ischemia]] or [[frostbite]] to the skin, it is recommended that the ice be placed within a towel or other insulating material before wrapping around the area.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}
Exceeding the recommended time for ice application may be detrimental, as it has been shown to delay healing.{{Citation needed|date=May 2013}}
=== Compression === Compression aims to reduce the [[edematous]] swelling that results from the inflammatory process. Although some swelling is inevitable, too much swelling results in significant loss of function, excessive pain and eventual slowing of blood flow through vessel restriction.{{Citation needed|date=September 2011}}
An [[elastic bandage]], rather than a firm plastic bandage (such as zinc-oxide tape) is required. Usage of a tight, non-elastic bandage will result in reduction of adequate blood flow, potentially causing [[ischemia]]. The fit should be snug so as to not move freely, but still allow expansion for when muscles contract and fill with blood.
Compression stockings or sleeves are a viable option to manage swelling of extremities with graduated compression (where the amount of compression decreases as the distance to the heart decreases). These garments are especially effective post-operatively and are used in virtually all hospitals to manage acute or chronic swelling, such as congestive heart failure.{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}
=== Elevation === Elevation aims to reduce swelling by increasing venous return of blood to the systemic circulation. This will result in less [[edema]] which reduces pain and/or swelling.{{citation needed|date=November 2013}}
==Variations== Variations of the acronym are sometimes used, to emphasize additional steps that should be taken. These include: * "RICE" - Rest, Immobilize, Cold, Elevate<ref>{{cite web |last1=American Red Cross |url=https://twitter.com/redcross/status/248782201485942785?lang=en |website=Twitter}}</ref> * "HI-RICE" – [[Fluid replacement|Hydration]], [[Ibuprofen]], Rest, Ice, Compression, and Elevation * "PRICE" – Protection, Rest, Ice, Compression, and Elevation<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mayoclinic.com/health/sprains-and-strains/DS00343/DSECTION=9 |title=Sprains and strains: Self-care - MayoClinic.com |accessdate=2007-08-15 |work=}}</ref><ref name="pmid17137000">{{cite journal |author=Ivins D |title=Acute ankle sprain: an update |journal=American Family Physician |volume=74 |issue=10 |pages=1714–20 |year=2006 |pmid=17137000 |doi=}}</ref><ref name="pmid18093299">{{cite journal |vauthors=Bleakley CM, O'Connor S, Tully MA, Rocke LG, Macauley DC, McDonough SM |title=The PRICE study (Protection Rest Ice Compression Elevation): design of a randomised controlled trial comparing standard versus cryokinetic ice applications in the management of acute ankle sprain [ISRCTN13903946] |journal=BMC Musculoskelet Disord |volume=8|page=125 |year=2007 |pmid=18093299 |doi=10.1186/1471-2474-8-125 |url=http://www.biomedcentral.com/1471-2474/8/125 |pmc=2228299}}</ref> * "PRICE" – Pulse (Typically Radial or Distal), Rest, Ice, Compression, and Elevation * "PRICES" – Protection, Rest, Ice, Compression, Elevation, and Support * "PRINCE" – Protection, Rest, Ice, [[Non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug|NSAIDs]], Compression, and Elevation<ref name="titleAnkle sprain - Yahoo! Health">{{cite web |url=http://health.yahoo.com/other-other/ankle-sprain/healthwise--te7580.html |title=Ankle sprain - Yahoo! Health |accessdate=2008-02-23 |work=}}</ref> * "RICER" – Rest, Ice, Compression, Elevation, and Referral<ref name="titleSmartPlay : Managing your Injuries">{{cite web |url=http://www.smasa.asn.au/smartplay/ouch/injury_manage/injury_info.html |title=SmartPlay : Managing your Injuries |accessdate=2008-05-28 |work=}}</ref> * "DRICE" – Diagnosis, Rest, Ice, Compression, and Elevation * "POLICE" – Protection, Optimal Loading, Ice, Compression, and Elevation<ref name=BJSM>{{cite web|last=C M|first=Bleakley|title=PRICE needs updating, should we call the POLICE?|url=http://bjsm.bmj.com/content/46/4/220.long|publisher=BMJ|accessdate=5 March 2012}}</ref>
==Alternatives== As the Cold or Ice component of RICE and its variations reduces blood flow to the injured area and delays healing,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.consumerreports.org/health/avoid-ice-for-a-sprained-ankle/|title=Why You Should Avoid Ice for a Sprained Ankle|work=Consumer Reports|access-date=2018-11-24|language=en-US}}</ref> some people argue that for certain types of injuries (such as damage to ligaments and tendons) a protocol that increases blood flow, such as MEAT (Movement, Exercise, Analgesics and Treatments), should be used instead.<ref name="Meat v. Rice">{{cite web|url=http://www.caringmedical.com/meat-vs-rice-treatment/|title=MEAT vs RICE treatmentwork=|deadurl=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130730131428/http://www.caringmedical.com/meat-vs-rice-treatment/|archivedate=30 July 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>{{medrs|date=January 2013}}
