{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}} {{Use British English|date=August 2015}} {{Infobox Museum |name = Shefton Museum |image = Armstrongbuilding.jpg |caption = The Armstrong Building, the former home of the Shefton Museum |imagesize = 200 |map_type = |map_caption = |coordinates = {{coord|54.9797|-1.6160|display=inline}} |established = {{start date|1956}} |dissolved = {{end date|2008}} |location = [[Newcastle upon Tyne]], [[England]], UK |type = Archaeology museum |visitors = |director = Miss [[Lindsay Allason-Jones]] |curator = Prof. Tony Spawforth |publictransit = [[Haymarket Metro station|Metro]] |network = Great North Museum |website = <!-- [http://www.ncl.ac.uk/shefton-museum/ www.ncl.ac.uk/shefton-museum] Site now inactive --> }}
'''The Shefton Museum of Greek Art and Archaeology''' was an [[archaeological]] museum at the [[University of Newcastle upon Tyne]], [[England]], which opened in 1956<ref name=about>{{cite web |url=http://www.ncl.ac.uk/shefton-museum/museum.html |title=About the Museum |publisher=Shefton Museum ([[Newcastle University]]) |accessdate=2008-04-24 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071025005324/http://www.ncl.ac.uk/shefton-museum/museum.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-10-25}}</ref> and closed in 2008. Its collections are now part of the [[Great North Museum]].
== History == The museum was located in the Department of Classics in the [[Armstrong Building]] of the main University campus. It was founded in 1956 by Professor Brian B. Shefton with a grant of £20 from the University's Rector, [[Charles Bosanquet (academic)|Charles Bosanquet]].<ref name=about/> Since then the collection has grown to over 800 objects.<ref name=about/> Professor B.B. Shefton was the curator until 1984 when his role was taken over by Professor Tony Spawforth.<ref name=about/> Shefton died on 25 January 2012, aged 92.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/culture-obituaries/art-obituaries/9153928/Professor-Brian-Shefton.html |title=Professor Brian Shefton |publisher=''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' |date=2012-03-09 |accessdate=2012-05-07}}</ref>
As part of the [[Great North Museum]] Project the Shefton collection, along with [[Museum of Antiquities]], was moved to the ''[[Hancock Museum|Great North Museum:Hancock]]''. On 18 April 2008 the museum closed in preparation for the relocation of its collections to the newly renovated Hancock Museum, which opened in May 2009.<ref name=last>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ncl.ac.uk/press.office/press.release/content.phtml?ref=1208183792 |title=Last chance to visit University Museums |publisher=Newcastle University |date=2008-04-14 |accessdate=2008-04-24 }}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
